»CL8:So, now we go over to my diplomatical
middle-way solution. I might as well
have dropped the first one, because as
stated a lot of times, I don't think
you will actually realize that one,
although that would be the best for
the scene, and it is not only my
opinion, but that of most sceners I
have talked with about this topic, we
simply do not need the masses, being
present together with them can only
diminish a sceneparty. So, this is a
compromise, being together with them,
but a little bit seperated from them.
It is a problematic and not so easy
compromise, and it is by far not
enough either, but let's take it one
step at a time. First of all: Who are
sceners and who are not? However, by
explicitly stating that Hall 1 is
reserved for sceners (that is, all
sceners get a place there, others will
have to move), and by placing the
best/fastest network in the other
halls, one can make Hall 1 more
serious. But, correct me if I'm wrong,
was that not precisely what you did
last time? It is not enough. Most
sceners sat in the upper half of the
hall last year, and the scener/lamer
(excuse my using this word for a
normal computerowner bringing with him
his PC, but in this regard, they do
count as lamers, so don't feel hit
here, hehe) ratio there was maybe 1/4,
that is one scener, 4 lamers. In Hall
3 it probably was 0/1xxx and in the
other halls 1/15-20 maybe, based on me
going around looking and chatting as
usual, but that is of course in no way
an exact estimate. I'm sorry, but I
can't see any real solution by doing
this. Some sceners and especially
normal but serious/creative computer
owners will choose to be seated in
other places, with a fast network, but
yes, most sceners would, if they knew
they could, choose to sit in one
place. I'm doubtful as to how that
will turn out though, since the ratio
still was 1/4 last year, up there.
Still, I heard some positive remarks
about this last year, but I think that
was because we are not at all
accustomed to ANY visible special
treatment on TP, so we get astonished
at all things, hehe. So, with this
solution, more needs to be done, to
make the scener feel special and
wanted. You can keep the entire TP
structure, but you must make the
scener feel in some way separated (one
could also say 'above') from the
masses, and you must make him feel
special. The first thing I can't see
how can be accomplished under this
solution, apart from making Hall 1
totally sceners only. There would
however be a lot of space left then
(there are maybe 500 attending
sceners? It feels like there are only
50-100, but I don't know anything
about PC sceners either), and as
stated, who is a scener and who is
not? I could, by extreme prejudice
maybe select who was,and who was not,
an Amiga scener, I know all the
groups, etc., but it is obvious that
this is not feasible at all, and
people would get angry, somewould get
treated unfairly, etc.. So, feeling
separated, if at all possible, is not
enough. Feeling special then. Yes, how
to do that? There are several points
here. Firstly, have a good and working
delivery system, which does NOT
misplace/delete entries and make sure
sceners are responsible for the
demolab (NOT Finnish sceners though,
hahah). Secondly, use the big screen!
And mostly/only use it for scenish
stuff. If the sceners are sitting in
front of it (which they will, if they
have most of hall 1), they will love
it, and not complain about the volume
(well, if it does not constantly play
loud anyway), but be happy that they
can see something that matters to
them. There was not much happening
demowise on the big screen apart from
the compos last year, although I
offered to do a demoshow, etc. Doing
that would be the spark that could
kindle the party-feeling for the
sceners really, if the mainfocus was
on such things. Thirdly, remove all
those LAME competitions that have
nothing with creativity or the scene
to do, or throw those competitions
into Hall 2 or 3. Let people gawk at
fast burgereaters in there ;) Instead,
make more scenish competitions, but do
not invent NEEDLESS competitions, like
all those different PC demo categories
of last year (one PC demo, accelerated
because everybody has an 'accelerated'
PC, and one JAVA compo, NO windows,
linux, DOS, lameOS, etc.
democompetitions!). On the MS, they
have had scene quiz's with people on
stage making fools of themselves
(heh), guess the tune compos, etc..
Might be sceners would appreciate
small, surprise competitions.
Fourthly, and maybe most important,
you should make sceners enter for, say
50-75% of the normal entrancefee. Yes,
take a deep breath again, hehe. There
are maybe 500 sceners attending as
said, you can do the math yourself,
the real problem is to know who's a
scener and who's not, but you'll have
to figure out a way of knowing that
anyway, if you want to have control
over who sits where in hall 1. Making
sceners get in cheaper would make them
feel special of course, and would
show the world that you treat the
people that made TP possible with
care, etc. I'm sure you could come up
with other ways to make the sceners
feel a little more special and wanted,
but I think you will have to do one or
more drastic thingsif you keep TP this
way instead of going for solution 1.
It is not enough to be a bit more
scener friendly, if you want to
salvage what's left and avoid ending
up like TG, you have to do something
semi-drastic at least. And then, you
mustgive it time to work too, because
at this years TP, there will probably
be even less sceners than last year,
due especially to last year.






»CL0:Ok, now over to miscellaneus things to
improve TP for sceners, no mattter
which solution you pick, as the last
header before concluding. Get an
invitro done for the 3 major systems,
make sure NOT to neglect the smaller
systems in the compo's, like the C64,
DON'T drop the 4k competition, don't
act too cool (I haaaate your closing
ceremonies), get a jury in most
competitions to sort out the worst
entries, give honest answers instead
of those standard answers I have
mentioned above and TAKE PART IN THE
